               <desc type="site-data" xml:lang="en">
                  <p source="#bibl000056-3">Kaiyuan Monastery (Kaiyuansi 開元寺) was originally built in the second
                     year of the <term ref="/keyword/k000022">Eastern Wei</term> Xinghe reign period (535) as
                     Jingguan Monastery (Jingguansi 凈觀寺). It underwent two renamings: first to Jiehui Monastery (Jiehuisi 解慧寺) during
                     the <term ref="/keyword/k000080">Sui</term> dynasty, and later to Kaiyuan
                     Monastery by imperial decree in the twenty-sixth year of the <term
                        ref="/keyword/k000082">Tang</term> Kaiyuan reign period (738).</p>
                  <p source="#bibl000056-2">According to the "Record of the Reconstruction of
                     Kaiyuan Monastery in Zhengding"(重修正定开元寺記) from the twenty-eighth year of the <term
                        ref="/keyword/k00051">Ming</term> Wanli reign period (1601), the original site had a front courtyard with a gate tower (menlou 門樓),  
                     Jialan Hall (Jialandian 伽蘭殿) on the left (east), Geigu Hall (Geigutang 給孤堂) to the right (west) and Vairocana Pavilion (Piluge 毘盧閣) at the back. 
                     Following this was the <placeName ref="/place/000199">bell tower</placeName> (zhonglou
                     鐘樓) on the left (east), brick pagoda (zhuanta 磚塔) on the right (west), and finally the Fachuan
                     (Dharma Boat) Main Hall (Fachuan zhengdian 法船正殿) at the far end. At the time
                     there were also Tianwang (Tianwangdian 天王殿) and Weituo
                     Halls (Weituodian 韋陀殿), covering a total area of approximately 9,000 square
                     meters.</p>
                  <p source="#bibl000056-3">Since the late<term ref="/keyword/k00070"> Qing</term>
                     dynasty, the monastery has gradually fallen into disrepair. Currently, only the
                     bell tower and the brick Sumeru Pagoda (Xumita 須彌塔), as well as stone pillars from the
                     Three-Gate Tower (sanmenlou 三門樓) of the <term ref="/keyword/k00082"> Tang</term>
                     dynasty, unearthed in recent years, remain. The layout of the pagoda and tower
                     facing each other in the center of the temple reflects the characteristics of
                     early monastery architecture.</p>
               </desc>
